objdescid.origination: William Blake author, inventor, delineator, colorist

objinfo.numberleaves: 73Leaves 10 and 11 (Objects 19-20 and 21-22 as numbered here) are two sections of a single leaf bearing a preexisting pencil sketch. Leaves 44 and 45 (Objects 87-88 and 89-90 as numbered here) are two sections of Blake's *Edward & Elenor* engraving; the engraving appears on Objects 88 and 89. Leaves 71-73 (Objects 141-42, 143-44, and 145-46 as numbered here) are fragments apparently taken from a notebook; the verso of leaf 73 (Object 146) is blank.
objinfo.medium: Pen and ink, watercolors, pencil, and charcoal and/or crayonThe rectos of leaves 22-68 and the verso of leaf 69 bear Blake's proof intaglio engravings for *Night Thoughts*.
objinfo.watermark: 1794 J Whatman (Objects 1-2, 9-10, 23-26, 31-32, 39-42, 51-52, 67-68, 77-82, 137-38 as numbered here); PARD (Objects 97-98, 109-10, 119-20 as numbered here); R (Objects 141-42 as numbered here)The "PARD" watermark may be for LEPARD 1803.
objinfo.binding: Objects 1-20 and 23-42 as numbered here appear to have been bound as a single group at one time, in several stages; Objects 43-84 and 111-12 as numbered here were bound separately.
objinfo.stabholes: Objects 1-20 and 23-42 as numbered here have seven holes: approximately 9.1 cm. from the top, 0.24 cm. below the first, approximately 1.1 cm. below the second, approximately 7.5 cm. below the third, approximately 0.8 cm. below the fourth, approximately 7.2 cm. below the fifth, and approximately 5.1 cm. below the sixth. Objects 43-84 and 111-12 as numbered here have three holes: approximately 15 cm. from the top, approximately 4.15 cm. below the first, and approximately 4.8 cm. below the second.

provenance.name: The British Library
provenance.note: Acquired directly from Blake by John Linnell probably late in Blake's life (in the 1820s), sold from Linnell's estate, Christie's, 15 March 1918, lot (to "Parsons"); donated anonymously to the British Museum 11 May 1918 and is now housed in the British Library.
